review: **spoiler alert** Strong setup that continued to rise with great depth of characters and then really leveled off for the second half of the book with **spoiler alert** Strong setup that continued to rise with great depth of characters and then really leveled off for the second half of the book with a lot of redundancy and little nuance. With the multiple voices I would have liked to have seen even more emotion come through. For example, the strong-willed and stubborn Julia - my imagination leads me to expect that she would have had a lot more "choice words" and would have helped us better understand how she REALLY felt that allowed her to easily walk away from her family for 25 years. I wanted to know more about how she actually achieved such power and financial success as a single mom in NYC in the 80's without the comfort and support of her family with whom she shared so much. As one of the central characters, I expected more, especially at the end when somehow all her anger, disappointment, etc. quickly melted away and she encouraged her daughter to reunite with her estranged father. Just like that? She is welcomed back by family and friends without awkwardness, tough conversations, tears, confusion? I'm left wanting to know much more about the thoughts and feelings of the sisters during such a traumatic event of their older sister abandoning them, turning her back to them. HOW does that happen? Instead, we got a lot of the same reflections about their childhood stories. A bit too perfect of an ending. ...more

author: McWhorter, John
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Having read this book, I can imagine what it must be like to experience Professor McWhorter's study on American linguistic history in person. In it, hHaving read this book, I can imagine what it must be like to experience Professor McWhorter's study on American linguistic history in person. In it, he challenges the reader to consider perceived legitimacy of languages. In his words, "English hasn't existed long enough to diverge into dozens of starkly distinct dialects as it has in Great Britain. Black English is America's only English dialect that combines being strikingly unlike standard English, centuries old, embraced by an ever wider spectrum of people, and represented in an ever-growing literature." Using examples like Scots grammar that is quite different from English grammar and that many would consider a different dialect of English, or "Kiezdeutsch" speakers in Germany who are capable of speaking standard German "when they have to". McWhorter touches on many topics in this compact book, including code switching, Ebonics, languages around the world, minstrel speech in America, the "N word", "blaccent", Harlem Renaissance and so much more. In my opinion, he convincingly explains the nuances and complexities of Black English as a legitimate speech variety and its cultural importance. ...more

review: Like many others, I find this to be a difficult book to . Primarily due to the fact that this is fictional book, yet so much of it is based on LLike many others, I find this to be a difficult book to . Primarily due to the fact that this is fictional book, yet so much of it is based on Lale and Gita's experiences in the concentration camp. First and foremost it is a love story. Given that Lale entrusted Heather Morris with his innermost descriptions of his war-time and post-war life experiences in 2003 after Gita had already passed, in many ways this book feels like a tribute to his everlasting adoration and love for her. So many times throughout the book Lale overcomes the most harrowing incidences that almost feel impossible. There is an overarching tone of hope, courage and determination that persists through the pages unlike any other WWII era book that I've read. Kudos to Morris for spending countless hours with Lale to really hear him and weave together this love story. What an honor that must have been. While the writing is a bit flat and even dry at times, it is nonetheless another important reminder about this unfathomable period in history. ...more

review: My reason for reading this book was to learn more about the Red Hat organizational culture as I’m a current job applicant. I was pleasantly surprised My reason for reading this book was to learn more about the Red Hat organizational culture as I’m a current job applicant. I was pleasantly surprised by how many real examples about employees, internal terminology, systems and internal projects were shared. Also impressed by Whitehurst’s sharing of his own learning journey, missteps and revelations. As he stated himself, he’s not an academic, and he wrote the book to more broadly share why the open source / participative leadership approach, with meritocracy at its core, is so valuable in modern organizations where the speed of change is perpetual. In my own experience working at more traditional, hierarchical and conventional companies, that leadership style and organizational culture is quite rare. While Whitehurst provides tips at the end of each chapter, and sprinkles in good analogies throughout, it’s still quite difficult for most people to incorporate what he’s advocating. Egos, traditions, burnout, lack of EQ are just some of the barriers. That said, I appreciate the openness of the book and examples of how other organizations utilize similar concepts. He also referenced many books and contemporary leaders. I will try to remember the OODA loop example he shared and the successful Swarm approach that came from an internal leader. His tips on what competencies are crucial include patience, high EQ, personal strength and growth mindset are helpful. ...more

review: Mish mash. That is what comes to mind when I think about this book. It was a mish mash of writing styles (part research paper, part magazine article, Mish mash. That is what comes to mind when I think about this book. It was a mish mash of writing styles (part research paper, part magazine article, part Wikipedia, part biography) that did not work well for me. The women featured in the first 15 chapters were certainly courageous, bold, and true standouts - and many of their stories actually have already been told despite the title of the book. It's a shame that the writing was so jumbled and lacked helpful footnotes. It would be truly amazing to learn more about some of these women in more detail. The last 3 chapters really threw me off as it was a regurgitation of what was already stated, and then a multitude of other modern day women (ie Elizabeth Smart, Queen Elizabeth, Malala Yousafzai) were featured in singular paragraphs. Felt awkward and contrived. Kudos to major general Eder for attempting to showcase these women to help ensure their places in history, but it really fell flat. ...more

review: I first read this play almost 30 years ago. Thankfully I kept the book to read and appreciate the story again, and to share with others. It’s a gem. II first read this play almost 30 years ago. Thankfully I kept the book to read and appreciate the story again, and to share with others. It’s a gem. It helps one think about values such as pride, faith, education, hard work, trust, and integrity. How do those values hold up in times of temptation, difficult choices, mistakes, prejudices and fear of failure? It’s an emotional and gut wrenching series of events and dialogues. One might start to build a certain impression of Walter and end up being pleasantly surprised about him in the end. While there is no Hollywood happy ending, given the harsh realities facing Black America - then and now - the ending does invoke feelings of hope, curiosity and contemplation. Unlike Mrs Johnson who seems to take pleasure in watching the family struggle, readers will ultimately be rooting for the family to stick together and live their shared values. ...more

review: **spoiler alert** Strong start, dismal finish. The through line started to disconnect as soon as Theo and Jess started their relationship. What really**spoiler alert** Strong start, dismal finish. The through line started to disconnect as soon as Theo and Jess started their relationship. What really was the point? Lots of cringy narratives and commentary. If only Brooks just stuck with the 1800’s storyline and developed the characters more thoroughly, it would have stayed strong. Jarret, his father, Scott, Viley, etc all could have been expanded more deeply. Some characters were introduced and then just disappeared. I’ll give credit for the Beautiful depictions of Lexington, lovely descriptions of the landscape, extensive vocabulary. Yet she ends up only dedicating three pages to detail Jarret’s escape from Kentucky in the Civil War to become a trusted agent of horse sales in Canada. We are left with an incomplete picture of the beloved trainer as well as how Lexington ended up in an attic despite being buried by Jarret. Much more should have been written about that rather than describing Theo and Jess’s interpersonal conflicts. Brooks’s journalistic approach could have been better put to use instead of trying to turn the book into a social justice commentary for which she missed the mark on deep and lived understanding. Much like the main characters (Kerewin, Simon Clare, and Joe), the structure of the book is fractured making it challenging at times to easily follow. Very smart book filled with inner most thoughts from each character, as well as many Maori words/phrases (the glossary in back is very useful). There were many references to “bones” throughout the book, yet in the end I’m unsure exactly the reason for the title itself. Does it have to do with the physical status that all three got to when they were separated after the murder of pedophile and Simon’s near death when cutting Joe? There were some encouraging moments where some characters seemed to evolve (Fareeda and Khaled acknowledging their mistakes, Deya applying for college). There were also too many loose ends for my taste (did Sarah ever return to her family home? Where did Isra get caught running away with the girls?). I applaud Rum for courageously putting her story out for all to read and question and judge. I also wish she spent a bit more time developing her characters and removing so much of the repetitiveness. ...more

review: Captivating, educational and at times gut-wrenching. This book introduced me to the horrors that took place at the Ravensbruck women's prison camp durCaptivating, educational and at times gut-wrenching. This book introduced me to the horrors that took place at the Ravensbruck women's prison camp during WWII and the absolutely unfathomable experiments done to the Polish women who were ultimately called "rabbits". It is obvious that Kelly spent years researching and even visited the camp as well as the family home in CT of the wonderfully generous Caroline Ferriday. While it is a fictional book, many of the people mentioned in the book were real. Overall a 4.5 rating for the writing and subject matter. Kelly was able to illustrate how Caroline's views and relationships changed over the years and how consistent others like Herta and Kasia were with their stances. Yet there were a few gaps in the story that I would have appreciated knowing about. Overall, a great read and a time in history I hope we never forget. ...more
